For those kind of limitations the constitution might need to be changed. In case a ordinary law states absolute limits it would be quite likely that the constitutional court challenge the law (either because it's a substantial contradiction to the universal character of the right to ask for asylum or as a challenge of Article 1 since the asylum seekers would be objectified as pure number). In other words: There is a good chance that such kind of law is going to be declared as invalid by the constitutional court. It wouldn't make sense to try to pass such a law since it would provoke an open fight within the conservative party and the social democrats, especially since there is a good chance that this law won't exist for too long. In order to make such kind of "threshold" sustainable, it needs to be implemented in the constitution (and even that might not be possible). However, there is simply no two third majority in the two chambers of the parliament (neither in Bundestag nor in Bundesrat) to do so.

I maintain my 1% for period b/w 13 March through 30th June. Simply wanted to provide justification as follows:

There will be no need for Germany to officially limit the number of migrants/refugees it accepts. The EU-Turkey deal and the closure of borders in the Balkans, along with some restrictions on what type of migrant Germany is accepting, will take care of the problem for them.

EU and Turkey new deal: Key points from the agreement Returns: All "irregular migrants" crossing from Turkey into Greece from 20 March will be sent back. Each arrival will be individually assessed by the Greek authorities. One-for-one: For each migrant returned to Turkey, a Syrian migrant will be resettled in the EU. Priority will be given to those who have not tried to illegally enter the EU and the number is capped at 72,000. Visa restrictions: Turkish nationals should have access to the Schengen passport-free zone by June. This will not apply to non-Schengen countries like Britain. Financial aid: The EU is to speed up the allocation of €3 bn ($3.3 bn; £2.3 bn) in aid to Turkey to help migrants. Turkey EU membership: Both sides agreed to "re-energise" Turkey's bid to join the European bloc, with talks due by July. http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-35840272 READ also: Refugees will be sent back across Aegean in EU-Turkey deal http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/18/refugees-will-be-sent-back-across-aegean-in-eu-turkey-deal _____NOTE______

So, the new EU-Turkey deal 1) returns all migrants who do not get asylum in Greece back to Turkey and 2) sets 72,000 cap on number of refugees EU (and therefore Germany, too) will accept from Turkey: http://blogs.wsj.com/briefly/2016/03/19/the-eu-turkey-migrants-deal-at-a-glance/
The proposed deal with Turkey saves Merkel from having to enact a formal cap

One can take a very cynical approach to this question. Just look at a map of Europe: Even if the EU-Turkey deals never materializes, even if Schengen is terminated and the EU falls apart: If countries like Austria, Slovakia, Hungary and Macedonia close their borders first, which I think is very likely, there is no need for Germany to do the same thing. Refugees will not be able to reach the German border anymore.

The proposed deal with Turkey, if concluded, will reduce migration by sea. The 1:1 swap (where every migrant caught in Greece is swapped for another already in Turkey that can enter the EU), should not overwhelm the EU as sea migration will dry up if the migrants know they will be returned. However, the EU will need to reach a deal on how these "swapped" migrants will be settled. In effect each country will be expected to sign up for a certain number. Will this be counted a cap? Will German pols push Merkel to enact some sort of cap? Hard to say.

The migrant, refugee & asylee crisis will either constrain or expand opportunities for the likelihood of a limitation policy in some form. It also simultaneously will influence the Federal Diet elections (for the date has not been confirmed). It is anticipated that elections will occur 2017. German law requires that the next election should take place on a Sunday between 46-48 months after the assembly's first sitting. Since the current Bundestag first sat on 22 October 2013, the latest date for the next election is 22 October 2017 (a Sunday). The earliest date is 27 August 2017, the first Sunday after 22 August. Elections to the Bundestag (Parliament) can occur earlier if a motion of no confidence in the Chancellor is passed by the current parliament. There is no doubt that the current political dynamic around the migrant (largely defined) crisis in the EU will be shaped (along with what happens in Germany) by the dynamics of border closings in Greece and the Balkan states (along with migrant/refugee limits in these frontline states)

This is my opening forecast and indeed my first GJP forecast ever so I plan to make many, perhaps daily adjustments to this judgement. For now I think one of the most relevant factors is the timing of the local, state and national elections. According to this site: http://www.wahlrecht.de/termine.htm the next national elections do not occur until Fall of 2017. There are local elections and state elections in the meantime but I am unclear how much influence they will have on national politics. Clearly I am assuming that Merkel's position is central to any actual change. I need to investigate her relationship to her party and her coalition partners in order to better predict what may move her. In general she is someone who is careful and empirical in her judgements. She also brings to this issue several kinds of legitimacy which matter in a German leader: she has a PhD in physics, she was born in the West but raised in the East after her father who was a Lutheran pastor accepted a position in the DDR. These biographical details matter, I think, because she has both an ethical and empirical manner in her approach to politics which I think is strongly influencing her approach to the matter of refugees and asylum seekers. Her decision to radically welcome Syrians and others surprised me given how unyielding she had been in the negotiations with the Greeks. I suspect she may now wish she had been more reserved in her judgement but nonetheless, I expect that she will expend considerable social and political capital to avoid utterly retracting her position. While there are factors that could push her and her partners to make some changes in the next six months (I need to do a great deal more reading on this before I can calculate probable behavior) the counterweight will be the relationship Germany has with Turkey, concerns about the rising number of casualties in the Syrian war and international attention which is not flagging. I'm also relatively certain that she will not respond to pressure from the far right. Indeed the more the far right protests, especially in places that were once the DDR, the more I would expect her to resist calls to limit the total number of refugees Germany will accept. I do expect that there will be more changes about the types of refugees or the locations from whence they may come but that has already happened. I look forward to reading comments from others on this topic.
